<topic id="dg-file-templates">
  <title>Creating New Document Templates for a Custom Framework</title>
  <prolog>
    <metadata>
      <keywords>
        <indexterm>Framework customization<indexterm>Configuring document
          templates</indexterm></indexterm>
      </keywords>
    </metadata>
  </prolog>
  <body>
    <p>You can create your own custom document templates and attach them to a custom <xref
        keyref="glossentry_framework"><term>framework</term></xref>. You can then <xref
        href="author-document-type-extension-sharing.dita">share the custom framework</xref> so that
      all users will have access to the templates in the <xref
        href="new-dialog-sa.dita#new-dialog-sa" product="author editor"><uicontrol>New</uicontrol>
        document wizard</xref><xref href="creating-from-templates.dita#creating-from-templates"
        product="authorEclipse editorEclipse"><uicontrol>New from templates</uicontrol>
        wizard</xref>.</p>
    <p>To create your own custom document template and have it appear in the new document wizard,
      follow these steps:<ol>
        <li>Create a new file and customize it to become a starting point for creating new files of
          this type.<note conkeyref="reusables-editing-documents/doc-template-note1"/></li>
        <li id="step2">Save the new template in a directory (for example, called
            <filepath>templates</filepath>) within your custom framework directory.<note
            conkeyref="reusables-editing-documents/doc-templates-note2"/></li>
        <li id="step3">Open the <xref href="the-document-type-dialog.dita#the-document-type-dialog"
              ><uicontrol>Document Type</uicontrol> configuration dialog box</xref> for that
          specific framework, go to the <xref href="document-type-templates-tab.dita"
              ><uicontrol>Templates</uicontrol> tab</xref>, and click the <image
            href="../img/Add16.png" placement="inline"/> button in the bottom-right corner to add
          your new directory to the list. It is recommended that the reference be made relative to
          the framework directory (for example, <filepath>${frameworkDir}/templates</filepath>).
          Binding to an absolute file (e. g.: <filepath>C:\some_dir\templates</filepath>) makes the
          association difficult to share between users.</li>
        <li>Click <uicontrol>OK</uicontrol> for all of the dialog boxes to save your changes.</li>
        <li>To test the template, open the new document wizard (<uicontrol><image
              href="../img/New16.png" id="image_hy1_zdp_sr" product="author editor"/><image
              href="../img/EclipseNew.png" id="image_nbd_fkf_wr"
              product="authorEclipse editorEclipse"/>New</uicontrol> toolbar button or <menucascade
            product="author editor">
            <uicontrol>File</uicontrol>
            <uicontrol>New</uicontrol>
          </menucascade><menucascade product="authorEclipse editorEclipse">
            <uicontrol>File</uicontrol>
            <uicontrol>New</uicontrol>
            <uicontrol>New from Templates</uicontrol>
          </menucascade>) and you should see your custom template in the folder for your custom
            <term>framework</term> (in the <uicontrol>Framework templates</uicontrol> section).</li>
      </ol></p>
  </body>
